[Event "The Vigorous Wormald Attack: A Practical White Repertoire vs. 1.e4 e5"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the Course!"]
[Date "2024.11.06"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C77"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41625718"]

{ Hello, everyone, and welcome! I'm Spanish International Master Alfonso Jerez, and this is my second Chessable course.

The topic of my first course [https://www.chessable.com/the-vigorous-alapin-sicilian/course/213707/] was my favorite weapon against the Sicilian Defense, the Alapin 2.c3. This time, we'll fight 1...e5, the most popular reply to 1.e4, with a repertoire based on non-critical lines, allowing us to surprise our opponents.

For many people, the Spanish or Ruy Lopez Opening evokes extremely long theoretical lines. However, I've done my best to simplify our repertoire, so playing it doesn't involve a massive effort.

The course is suitable for all levels and avoids entering critical theoretical debates. Case in point: my recommendation against the Petrov Defense will be 3.d4 instead of the main move 3.Nxe5 and we'll play the Ruy Lopez sidestepping the Berlin Defense by meeting 3...Nf6 with 4.d3 steering the game into our Qe2 setups, thus lightening our study workload.

In this repertoire, you'll find very solid variations that are especially suitable for games against strong opponents and riskier lines that can prove very effective at the club level, as well as in rapid or blitz games. That's why I have included two Quickstarter Guides, intending to cater to both playing styles. } 1. e4 { Let's dive into the content! Here's a map of our repertoire. } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 ( 2...d5 { This move introduces the Elephant Gambit, which will be covered in chapter 1. [/course/259787/3] It's not a formidable weapon for Black, but we need to know it to avoid nasty surprises. } ) ( 2...f5 { The Latvian Gambit and other rare options for Black are also studied in chapter 1. [/course/259787/3] } ) ( 2...d6 { The solid Philidor Defense is the topic of chapter 2. [/course/259787/4] } ) ( 2...Nf6 { The Petrov Defense is one of the most important systems we'll face after 2.Nf3 and we'll study it in chapter 3. [/course/259787/5] Here, } 3.d4 { This is my recommendation because I consider it the best way to fight for the advantage. } ) 
3. Bb5 { In recent times, the Spanish Opening or Ruy Lopez has lost popularity at the Grandmaster level. This could work in our favor because our opponents will be better prepared against the trendy Italian, the Scotch, or the tricky gambits. } a6 ( 3...Nge7 { The Cozio Defense and other early alternatives for Black are covered in chapter 4. [/course/259787/6] } ) ( 3...Nf6 { Nowadays, the Berlin Defense is a trendy system, but we'll neutralize with } 4.Qe2 { when whatever Black plays won't have independent value and we'll stay within our repertoire. } ) 
4. Ba4 Nf6 ( 4...d6 { The Modern Steinitz is perhaps the most important alternative to } ) ( 4...Nf6 { , and we'll find it in chapter 5 [/course/259787/7] with the rest of the sidelines. } ) 
5. Qe2 ( { This introduces the Wormald Attack, the core of our course. My intention when I picked this system instead of } 5.O-O { followed by Qe2 was twofold. On the one hand, we avoid some lines, such as the Open Spanish } 5...Nxe4 { . My second goal was to keep the door open to h3 and g4 setups to launch a kingside attack. One of the perks of a stable center is that our king stays safe in such scenarios where we have delayed castling. } ) b5 
6. Bb3 Bc5 { This move can be considered Black's main weapon against 5.Qe2 and will be covered in chapter 7. [/course/259787/9] } ( { Chapter 6 [/course/259787/8] is devoted to } 6...Be7 { , one of Black's main ideas in the Ruy Lopez. The chapter also addresses other secondary options for Black. } 7.c3 { This is my recommendation against 6...Be7 and, as a rule of thumb, we'll play a quick d4 unless Black goes for the central break ...d5, when we'll switch to d3-setups. } ) 
7. c3 { Against Black's setup with ...Bc5, my recommendation is still c3, but then I think playing with d3 instead of d4 is more principled.

Before we jump into the theory section, I've added an extra chapter about thematic strategic ideas [/course/259787/10] in the Spanish that will help us understand this opening, and to close the course, a selection of model games [/course/259787/11] illustrating the variations studied in our repertoire. These bonus chapters complement our opening study and allow you to see how the typical plans are developed in practical play so you can handle the middlegame and the endgame when the theory ends.

As usual, I encourage you to share any doubts or questions in the course forum or the specific positions. I hope you all enjoy the course. Best of luck fighting 1...e5! } *

