1. -- {[%csl Ra6,Gc5]} { Changing our pawn structure by allowing the bishop trade on b3 and recapturing axb3 helps open the a-file a and thus weaken Black's a6-pawn.

After advancing our pawn to b4, our structure is very solid; meanwhile, Black's a6-weakness can never get support from other pawns.

There are other factors to consider. For example, White should always prefer to trade Black's light-squared bishop on b3 instead of a black knight.

The basic idea is to trade some pieces. Then, the c5-square can be a fantastic outpost for a knight.

In general, if we can land a knight on c5, we'll have a very superior endgame, as long as we can prevent Black's liberating move ...a5. } *

