1. -- {[%cal Ya4b5,Ga4a5,Gc3c4]} { This strategic idea consists of fixing the queenside structure by means of b4 to follow up with a4 and not only weaken Black's b-pawn but also gain control of the a-file. Sometimes, we will use the opposite order, going a4 first and then b4, aiming to prevent Black from playing ...b4 and using the c5-square.

We will eventually control the a-file because we will be the ones to decide when the exchange on b5 takes place, and we'll have more space than Black to double rooks behind the a-pawn.

Another option is closing the queenside with a5 and then going for the c4 break to weaken the a6-pawn again.

On the other hand, if Black takes on a4, their newly-created isolated pawn on a6 will be a problem for the rest of the game. } *

