[White "Typical Plans in the Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Sacrifices on the h6-square"]
[Date "2024.11.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/5pp1/7B/4pN2/4P3/7P/5PP1/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41625750"]

1. -- {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Gf1g3,Gg3f5,Ge3f5,Yg1f3,Yf3h4,Yh4f5][%csl Gf5]} { Another thematic idea in the Ruy Lopez is a piece sacrifice on h6.

Very often, one of our knights will reach the f5-square via b1-d2-f1-e3 or b1-d2-f1-g3 or even g1-f3-h4-f5. That achievement allows us to generate a powerful attack on Black's kingside.

Therefore, and exploiting the fact that our opponent will struggle to transfer units to that sector with the center closed, some piece sacrifices (whether bishops or knights) on the h6-square become a possibility. In such scenarios, White can easily accumulate forces on the kingside, e.g., with a rook lift on the third rank or bringing the queen over via g4, h5, or, if possible, d2-h6.

For these ideas to work, the center must be closed with some space advantage for White thanks to the more advanced central pawns on e4 and d5. } *

