[Black "Pawn structure with a5 against ...b4"]
[Date "2024.11.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "8/2p5/p2p4/P3p3/1p2P3/3P4/1PP5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41625754"]

1. -- {[%cal Gc2c3,Gb2c3][%csl Rb4,Ra6]} { In this pawn structure, typical in the Ruy Lopez, we have managed to isolate Black's queenside pawns so they are vulnerable for the rest of the game.

Sometimes, we will go for c3 to open the b-file and target the a6-pawn, which will be a serious weakness in this type of position.

Another possible approach is using the now available b3- and c4-squares and maneuvering there with our knights.

If White gets the d4 break and Black is forced to take, then a future ...c5 is off the table because it would dramatically weaken d6, a backward pawn in that scenario, and Black would face too many structural issues. } *

[Event "The Vigorous Wormald Attack: A Practical White Repertoire vs. 1.e4 e5"]
