8. Ba2 ( { The most precise move order. I used to play } 8.Qe2?! { , but this move order is seriously flawed. } 8...exd4 9.Nxd4 Re8 { Suddenly, our queen is in trouble. Black intends ...d5. } 10.Ba2 Bf8 { Putting pressure on the d-file. } 11.Qf3 Nc5 { I had this position once with the white pieces, thinking I would secure an advantage with } 12.Bg5 { but the Spanish GM Herminio Herraiz had this nasty surprise for me: } 12...h6! 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Qxf6 gxf6 15.Rfe1 Bg7 { Black has clear compensation for their wrecked structure, mainly thanks to the bishop pair. The ...f5 push is a very strong idea. I managed to bail out with a draw, but I can't recommend this line. } ) b6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc8b7,Gb6b5]} { If Black wants to play ...b5, this is the way. } ( 8...a6 { is met by } 9.a5 { . Preventing ...b6 is always nice. } ) 
9. Qe2 Qc7 
10. Rd1 Bb7 
11. h3!? { Waiting for Black to commit a rook to e8 before jumping to h4 with our knight. Sidestepping any future back-rank issues will always come in handy. } Rae8 
