1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. Bb5 a6 
4. Ba4 Nf6 
5. Qe2 { The Wormald Attack is a system where we postpone castling to wait and see what our opponent does first. Only when they commit their position will we decide whether to play d3 or d4 and whether to castle or go h3-g4 instead. The queen on e2 protects the pawn, and we save a tempo on Re1. Also, the queen steps out of the d-file, which is likely to be opened and is a much more suitable place for a white rook. } b5 { Black can play ...b5 now, or after ...Be7. Even playing it after ...d6 is possible. They are just transpositions. } 
6. Bb3 Be7 { This is one of Black's main options to fight the Wormald Attack, and will have its own chapter. [/course/259787/8] Black wants to play ...d6 and castle short. } ( { However, this is not as critical as } 6...Bc5 { , which we'll cover in another chapter. [/course/259787/9] } ) ( 6...Bb7 7.c3 Be7 { and now, if White doesn't want to transpose, } 8.d3 { is possible. } { 8.d4 d6 will end up transposing into other lines after both sides castle. } ) 
7. c3 { I like starting with this to enable Bc2 but also to toy with the d4 idea. Also, we may prepare h3 and g4 without castling. } d5 { This is an excellent gambit not worth accepting. } 
8. d3 ( { Accepting the gambit doesn't look sensible. } 8.exd5?! Nxd5 9.Nxe5 Nxe5 10.Qxe5 Nf6 { reminds me of the Marshall Gambit but in a worse version for White! Black enjoys quite superior development, and I don't know why our queen is standing on an open file. } ) O-O 
9. O-O Re8 {[%cal Ge8e2]} { Black wants to take their bishop to f8 and protect the e-pawn with the rook. } 
10. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Rd5]} { Putting pressure on the d-pawn. } Be6 
11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1g3]} { The standard plan of the d3-setups in the Ruy Lopez. } h6 
12. Bxf6 { This may look strange, but it allows us to increase the pressure on the d-pawn. } Bxf6 
13. Rad1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Gd3d4][%csl Rd5]} g6 
14. h4 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1g3,Gh4h5]} { White's idea is to push h5 and force Black to play ...g5 and weaken the f5-square. We also exploit the fact that the black queen is busy protecting d5 and can't capture the h-pawn. } *

