5. Qe2 {[%mdl 32768]} { The Wormald Attack is a system where we postpone castling to wait and see what our opponent does first. Only when they commit their position will we decide whether to play d3 or d4 and whether to castle or go h3-g4 instead. The queen on e2 protects the pawn, and we save a tempo on Re1. Also, the queen steps out of the d-file, which is likely to be opened and is a much more suitable place for a white rook. } b5 { Black can play ...b5 now, or after ...Be7. Even playing it after ...d6 is possible. They are just transpositions. } 
6. Bb3 g6?! ( { This is typical. Black wants to fianchetto their bishop and castle short. } 6...Bb7 7.c3 Be7 { and if White doesn't want to transpose, } 8.d3 { is possible, while } { 8.d4 d6 will end up transposing into other lines after both sides castle. } ) 
7. d4 { The best choice, as Black will still need some time to complete their development. } Qe7 { The only reasonable move for Black. } 
8. O-O Bg7 
9. dxe5 { This trade is important to pave the way for the central pawns. } Nxe5 
10. Nxe5 {[%cal Gf2f4]} { After this, our f-pawn is ready to roll. } Qxe5 
11. f4! { We push our pawns, threatening the enemy pieces. } Qd4+ ( { White wins a piece after } 11...Qxe4? 12.Qxe4+ Nxe4 13.Bd5 { with the double attack. } ) 
12. Kh1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Ga1d1]} { White is better because the e5 push is coming. } *

