[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41749759"]

1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 
2. Nf3 Qe7?! {[%csl Rf8]} { The Brazilian Defense has always had a terrible reputation, which doesn't surprise me at all. Placing your queen in front of your king while hindering your bishop's development can never be a good idea. } 
3. Bc4 h6 { Having to play ...h6 on your third move is sad, but Black wants to prevent any white piece from landing on the g5-square. } ( 3...Nf6 4.d4 { and Black's position looks a mess. } ) 
4. d4 d6 
5. O-O Nf6 
6. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4]} { Restricting Black's light-squared bishop. } c6 ( 6...g5 7.Nc3 { This is good for White, who enjoys an obvious development lead. } ) 
7. Re1 Nbd7 { Black is playing à la Philidor, but his grounded bishop on f8 is a serious problem. } 
8. a4! {[%cal Ga4a5,Rb7b5]} { A multipurpose move, as it prevents Black from gaining space on the queenside with ...b5 and initiates the plan we'll see in the game, in connection with White's next move. } a5 { This may not be a good idea, but allowing White to push a5 wasn't a pleasant scenario. } 
9. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3]} { Now, we can see White's dark-squared bishop will be developed on a3, from where it will torture the black pieces. } g6? { This is already a grave mistake. Black's bishop shouldn't leave the f8-a3 diagonal. } 
10. Ba3 {[%csl Rd6]} { White's position is completely harmonious, whereas Black struggles to find any coordination. } Qd8 
11. Nbd2 Be7 { The only reasonable development plan. } 
12. Bf1!! {[%cal Gd2c4]} { Vacating the c4-square for the knight. } exd4 
13. Nxd4 O-O 
14. Nc4 {[%csl Rd6]} { Rizouk's play has been excellent, and White has an enormous advantage. It's hard to imagine how Black will save his d6-pawn. } Ne5 
15. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd2h6,Gf2f4][%csl Rd6]} g5 
16. Rad1 Re8 
17. Qc3 {[%cal Ga3d6,Gd1d8,Gc3f6][%csl Re5,Rf6]} { Again, Rizouk plays the best move. White's queen steps out so the rook can be aligned with the enemy queen. } Nxc4 ( 17...Qc7 18.Nxe5 dxe5 19.Nb5 Qb6 20.Nd6 Bxd6 21.Bxd6 Nd7 22.Bc4 { followed by Qf3 and a crushing attack on f7. } ) 
18. Bxc4 Bf8 
19. Qf3 {[%csl Rf6]} d5 { This wouldn't save Black, but it is a good attempt at complicating the game. } 
20. Bxf8 Kxf8 
21. exd5 Rxe1+ 
22. Rxe1 cxd5 
23. Bd3 {[%cal Gh3h4]} { The simplest. White resumes his kingside attack. } Qd6? { This loses on the spot, but Black was beyond salvation. } ( 23...Bd7 24.Re5 { intending h4 and Qf4 decides the game. } ) 
24. Ne6+ {[%csl Rf6]} Bxe6 
25. Qxf6 Ke8 ( 25...Kg8 26.Qxh6 { The immediate threat could be simply Qh7 and Qh8. } 26...Rd8 27.Rxe6 Qxe6 28.Qxg5+ { winning the rook. } { 27...fxe6 leads to a forced mate. 28.Bh7+ Kf7 29.Qg6+ Ke7 30.Qg7+ Ke8 31.Bg6 or 28...Kh8 29.Bg6+ Kg8 30.Qh7+ Kf8 31.Qf7 } ) 
26. Bb5+ {[%cal Gf6h8][%csl Ra8]} { And Black loses the a8-rook. A simple and effective way to face the Brazilian Defense. } 1-0

