4. Nf3 Nbd7 
5. Bc4 Be7 
6. O-O O-O 
7. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc4a2]} { A multipurpose move that vacates the a2-square for the bishop to retreat and challenges Black's queenside expansion plans. } c6 
8. Ba2 b6 { The best way to develop the c8-bishop. } 
9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf1d1]} a6 
10. Rd1 Qe8? {[%csl Rf8]} { I have never seen merit in this move. Of course, the queen is feeling comfortable on the same file as the white rook, but c7 was the most suitable square. The queen on e8 disturbs the f8-rook. } ( 10...Qc7 11.h3 Bb7 12.Nh4 { As soon as the bishop moves to b7, our knight will head towards f5. } ) 
11. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5]} Bb7? { Black should have taken on d4. } ( 11...exd4 12.Rxd4 d5 13.exd5 Bc5 14.Rd1 { White is better anyway, but this was the only sensible approach. } ) 
12. Nf5 Kh8 
13. Bg5 {[%cal Ge2f3]} { White starts bringing pieces near the enemy king. } b5 
14. dxe5 dxe5 
15. Qf3 { The queen joins the attack as well. } Nc5 
16. Rd6!! {[%csl Rf6]} { A brilliant sacrifice, although the rook is immune to capture. } Ng8 ( 16...Bxd6 17.Nxg7! Kxg7 18.Qxf6+ Kg8 19.Bh6 { and checkmate is forced. } ) 
17. Bxe7 Nxe7 
18. Nxg7!! {[%cal Gf3f6]} { Another elegant sacrifice that wraps the game. } Kxg7 
19. Qf6+ Kg8 
20. Qg5+ {[%cal Gg5e5]} Ng6 { This won't save Black. } ( 20...Kh8 21.Qxe5+ Kg8 22.Qxc5 { and White wins. } ) 
21. Rxg6+! { Removing the last defender. } hxg6 
22. Qxg6+ {[%cal Ra2g8]} Kh8 
23. Qh6+ { The black king is all alone. } Kg8 
24. Re1!! {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3g3]} { And the rook will land on the g3-square to deliver checkmate. } Qd7 
25. Re3 Qg4 { Sad necessity. } 
26. Rg3 Qxg3 
27. hxg3 { Materially speaking, the game is still open. However, White has multiple threats. } b4 
28. Qg6+ Kh8 
29. Qh5+ Kg8 
30. Qg6+ Kh8 
31. Bxf7 {[%cal Gg6h6]} -- ( { Rowson resigned due to } 31...Rxf7 32.Qxf7 bxc3 33.b4!! { and Black can't save the bishop. An attacking masterpiece by the Scottish Grandmaster Paul Motwani. } )
