11. Qh5 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gh5h7][%csl Rh7]} g6 ( 11...h6 12.Bxh6 { This sacrifice is a no-brainer: the black king has no defenders on sight. } 12...gxh6 13.Qxh6 Re8? { This leads to a forced mate. } 14.Bh7+ Kh8 15.Bg6+ Kg8 16.Qh7+ Kf8 17.Qxf7 ) 
12. Qh6 Re8 {[%cal Gc5f8]} { The only chance to bring the bishop to the defense. } 
13. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} Bf8 ( 13...Be7? 14.Bf6 Bxf6 15.exf6 Rxe1+ 16.Rxe1 { And Black can't stop the double mating threat on g7 and e8. } ) 
14. Qh4 Qd7 {[%cal Gd7g4]} { Intending to trade queens. } 
15. Rab1 {[%csl Rb7]} { White wants to stop ...Qg4. } Rb8 ( 15...Qg4 { was met by } 16.Qxg4 Bxg4 { . } ) 
16. c4 {[%cal Gd3c4]} { The idea is to improve the structure and gain the c4-square for the white bishop. } d4 ( 16...dxc4 17.Bxc4 Qg4 18.Bxf7+!! { A beautiful sacrifice that exploits the vulnerability of the f7-point now that the queen is gone. } 18...Kxf7 19.Qxh7+ Bg7 20.Bh6 Rg8 21.Bxg7 Rxg7 22.Qh8 { with the powerful threat e6 followed by Rb3-Rf3. } ) 
17. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5]} { White is threatening f5. } Qc6 ( 17...Qg4 18.Qf2 { The d-pawn is loose. } 18...c5 19.h3 Qd7 20.f5 { with a crushing attack. } ) 
18. Bf6 Bg7 
19. f5! {[%cal Gf6g7,Gf5f6]} Qc5 
20. Bxg7 Kxg7 
21. Qf6+ {[%cal Ge5e6]} ( 21.f6+?! { Giving this move a question mark wouldn't be fair because the position is still won for White, but there were simpler ways. } 21...Kh8 22.Qh6 Qf8 { Black is still lost, but there's no checkmate. } ) Kf8 ( 21...Kg8 22.e6 fxe6 23.fxg6 { with a crushing attack. } ) 
22. e6 { Black resigned, as checkmate is coming. When you hear the Petrov only leads to boring play, take a look at this game, and you'll see how things can get spicy. } 1-0

