1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 
3. d4 { This is my recommendation against the Petrov Defense. } exd4 
4. e5 { Before taking on d4, we force the black knight to move. } Ne4 
5. Qxd4 {[%csl Re4]} { Trying to win development tempi by attacking enemy pieces is always a good idea in the opening. } d5 
6. exd6 Nxd6 {[%cal Rf8d6]} { We have reached a symmetrical structure, but Black will struggle to develop their kingside due to their knight on d6. } 
7. Nc3 Nc6 
8. Qf4 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1c1]} { This looks like an odd square for the queen, but it is perfectly safe from harassment from the black pieces. } g6 { Akopian goes for the kingside fianchetto and is very likely to castle short. } 
9. Be3 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Ge1c1]} { Meanwhile, Ivanchuk wants to castle queenside, steering the game to an opposite-side castling position. } Bg7 
10. O-O-O O-O { Finally, we reach an opposite-side castling position where, as usual, time is of the essence when it comes to attacking the enemy king. } 
11. h4! { It's only logical that White wants to launch a kingside attack. We covered this in the Petrov chapter. [/variation/41694860/#/11/w] } h6 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg6g5]} { If Black can meet h5 with ...g5, White's attack will hardly succeed. } ( 11...h5 12.Bb5 { with the idea of taking on c6 followed by Bd4 to trade dark-squared bishops looks good for White. } ) 
12. Bc5 {[%cal Gc5d6,Gd1d6,Gf4d6][%csl Rd6]} ( { Perhaps } 12.Bb5 { might be an alternative. } ) Be6 
13. Bb5! {[%cal Gb5c6,Gc5d4]} a6 
14. Bxc6 { Ivanchuk already wanted to trade on c6 to follow up with Bd4 and exchange dark-squared bishops. Therefore, encouraging him with ...a6 is not a good call. } bxc6 
15. Bd4! { Once the dark-squared bishops have been traded, Black's castle will be completely vulnerable. } ( 15.Bxd6?? { would be a grave mistake. } 15...cxd6 16.Rxd6 Qb8 { Suddenly, only Black is attacking here. } ) f6 
16. Bc5 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gh1e1]} { The bishop simply frees the way for the white rook, but trading on d6 is not part of the plan. } Rf7 
17. Rhe1 Bd7 
18. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4e6]} ( 18.Ne4 { also seems to give White excellent play, with the idea of taking on d6 but keeping the dark-squared bishop on the board. } ) Qc8 
19. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3g6][%csl Rg6]} Nb7 ( 19...Kh7 20.Bxd6 cxd6 21.Ne4 { The threat Nxd6 is very strong. } ) 
20. Na4 {[%cal Rc8b7,Rc8d7,Ga4c5]} { There is no need to move the bishop, and Black's position is clearly stuck. } g5 
21. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3f7,Ge1e7]} { Re7 is a lethal threat. } Na5 
22. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3g6]} Nb7 
23. Re2 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge2e7]} { Clear and simple: White will double rooks on the e-file and invade the 7th rank. } Rb8 
24. Rde1 Nd6 
25. Qg6 {[%cal Ge2e7]} { Now, the threat of invading the 7th rank becomes a reality. } ( 25.Re7 Rxe7 26.Rxe7 Qd8 { and Black keeps some hopes of saving the game. } ) Qd8 
26. g4? {[%cal Rf6f5]} { Trying to stop the liberating move ...f5, but this is not the most accurate. That's a pity. So far, Ivanchuk had played a masterpiece. } ( 26.Ba3! { With the idea of Nc5 and Nce6 was enough to secure the victory. } ) f5! 
27. gxf5 Nxf5? ( 27...gxh4! { Black's only saving move, intending to follow up with ...Qg5 trading queens. } 28.Rg1 Nxf5 { and, although White has better prospects, play has become very complicated. } ) 
28. Nxc6 {[%cal Gc6b8,Gc6d8]} { Ivanchuk doesn't miss his chance. } Bxc6 
29. Qxc6 {[%cal Ge2e8]} Qd7 
30. Qxd7 { The simplest. } Rxd7 
31. hxg5 hxg5 
32. Re6 {[%cal Ge6a6,Ge6g6][%csl Ra6,Rg5]} { White is not only a pawn up, but all the black pawns are weak. } a5 
33. Ra6 Rd5 
34. Rxa5 { With two extra pawns, the game is decided. } Nd4 
35. Ra6 Nf3 
36. Re7 {[%cal Ga6g6][%csl Rg7]} Rbd8 {[%cal Gd5d1]} 
37. c3 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gc2b3,Gb3a3]} { Stopping the mate. } Rd1+ 
38. Kc2 R1d2+ 
39. Kb3 Rb8+ 
40. Ka3 { Now the white king is safe. } Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4]} 
41. b3 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ga6g6,Ge7c7]} { Once the mating threat has vanished, Black has no reason to play on.

Fantastic positional play by Ivanchuk. } 1-0

