{ Tiviakov is one of the biggest experts in the Wormald Attack, and we should always pay special attention to his games because they are full of interesting insights. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. Bb5 a6 
4. Ba4 Nf6 
5. O-O ( { My recommendation in the course is starting with } 5.Qe2 { to keep the option of playing without short castle depending on Black's choice of variation, though. } ) Be7 
6. Qe2 b5 
7. Bb3 d6 { By transposition, we have reached the 6...Be7 chapter [/course/259787/8] in our course. } 
8. c3 { Playing c3 before committing to d3 or d4 is an interesting and very flexible idea. White keeps both options open. } O-O 
9. Rd1 {[%cal Gd2d4]} { This move is usually a sign that White wants to play d4. } Na5 
10. Bc2 c5 
11. d4 { One of the most popular positions in the Wormald Attack. } Qc7 
12. d5 { In this variation, we need to remember that we should only close the center if Black has already played ...c5 so they don't have the ...c6 break. With this push, we secure some space advantage for the rest of the game. } Bd7 
13. b3 {[%cal Ra5c4,Rc4b6,Gc5c4,Gb3b4]} { We're ready to close the queenside by meeting any advance from the black pawns with c4 or b4. } Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 
14. h3 g6 { Black intends to go ...f5. } 
15. Bh6! { I like this move a lot. White transfers this bishop to the kingside, where it will pin the enemy knight on g7. } Ng7 {[%csl Rf8,Rg7]} 
16. Nbd2 f5? { Black goes for the thematic break, but this is ill-timed. } 
17. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e6]} { This was White's idea. His bishop on h6 was preventing Black from playing ...h6 before ...f5 to stop this knight jump to g5. } ( { Opening up with } 17.exf5 gxf5 18.Ng5 { also with good kingside attacking prospects, is my recommendation [/variation/41695629/#/18/w] in the course. } ) Qd8? ( 17...f4 { closing the kingside was Black's only chance. } 18.a4 c4 19.b4 Nb7 20.Ra2 { with the idea of Ra1. This is better for White. } ) 
